**Abstract:**
Extensive research notes dated August 14, 1991, titled "Tithenai ta Phainomena," analyzing the debate between Owen and Nussbaum on how Aristotle "sets down the appearances" for scientific investigation. The document explores whether Aristotle uses one method (Nussbaum: always starting from "ta legoumena," what the many and wise say) or two (Owen: Baconian empirical observation vs. dialectical/conceptual). The author develops his own insight that "experience" has different meanings depending on whether it refers to observation or exposure, with significant consequences for theoretical and practical sciences. Argues that the intellectualistic fallacy consists in confusing practical knowledge (agent coping with world) with theoretical/explanatory knowledge (researcher seeking understanding).

**AI Recommendation:** Major methodological essay for the Chantilly project; develops the crucial distinction between observation and exposure that underlies the theoretical/practical confusion.

